1
00:00:01,617 --> 00:00:05,022
Tonight I'm going to talk about the second and third noble truths.

2
00:00:06,003 --> 00:00:12,455
The second truth states that desire is the cause of dukkha and the injunction is to let go of desire.

3
00:00:13,496 --> 00:00:21,650
The third truth states that there is an end to dukkha with the injunction to realize this for ourselves.

4
00:00:21,631 --> 00:00:28,405
These truths manifest more clearly as we learn to experience the twelve links in the process that leads to dukkha.

5
00:00:29,486 --> 00:00:32,692
These are described in the Wheel of Dependent Origination.

6
00:00:33,674 --> 00:00:37,463
Each link depends on all the previous links having been made.

7
00:00:38,235 --> 00:00:40,521
We chant these 12 steps every morning.

8
00:00:40,561 --> 00:00:46,031
It all starts with avicca, usually translated as ignorance.

9
00:00:46,813 --> 00:00:50,841
We often hear that word as an insult, but that's not what is intended here.

10
00:00:50,881 --> 00:00:55,991
Instead, it means we don't fully understand what causes suffering.

11
00:00:57,237 --> 00:01:04,552
One interpretation of this teaching is to see it happening over multiple lifetimes, with each life influencing the next.

12
00:01:05,935 --> 00:01:16,798
It's also possible to see the wheel turning again and again within our lifetime, our incomplete understanding of the Dhamma leading us into dukkha at many stages in life.

13
00:01:17,977 --> 00:01:22,763
We can even see it turning within the minutiae that we study in meditation practice.

14
00:01:23,724 --> 00:01:32,936
Each breath, each footstep, each mood, emotion, thought, to the extent that these emerge from avijja, they result in dukkha.

15
00:01:35,120 --> 00:01:38,364
Bhante stresses that avijja is a blameless ignorance.

16
00:01:39,144 --> 00:01:43,751
We didn't create ourselves in this ignorant state, so we're not to blame for our predicament.

17
00:01:44,873 --> 00:01:46,734
At heart, we are innocents.

18
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:49,962
Most of us will admit to avijja.

19
00:01:50,864 --> 00:02:01,203
Even if we've studied the Dhamma and are convinced by the argument that greed leads to suffering, we can happily scoff an ice cream, telling ourselves we'll practice renunciation tomorrow.

20
00:02:02,346 --> 00:02:12,063
And when someone pushes our buttons, we still find ourselves reacting, despite the fact that we've heard and read countless teachings on the benefits of equanimity.

21
00:02:14,068 --> 00:02:20,795
Once we fully understood the teachings, ignorance will be eliminated and the wheel will no longer get a chance to turn.

22
00:02:20,855 --> 00:02:26,121
In the meantime, however, avijja allows sankaras to emerge.

23
00:02:27,883 --> 00:02:33,489
Sankaras are the drives which push us into and through our lives.

24
00:02:34,569 --> 00:02:40,836
These include greed, hatred and delusion, the strong forces which propel us towards dukkha.

25
00:02:42,502 --> 00:02:52,093
We also have beautiful Sankara, for example Metta, which means love or goodwill, as well as all the factors of enlightenment and spiritual faculties.

26
00:02:53,436 --> 00:02:57,501
In their purest form, these are not linked with Avicca, but with wisdom.

27
00:02:58,581 --> 00:03:00,925
Thus, they do not cause the wheel to turn.

28
00:03:00,985 --> 00:03:03,448
They don't propel us into dukkha.

29
00:03:05,009 --> 00:03:09,675
It's only the Sankara related to greed, hatred and delusion that turn the wheel.

30
00:03:11,360 --> 00:03:16,265
So far, we have ignorance and an unskillful Sankara beginning to roll the wheel.

31
00:03:16,306 --> 00:03:22,054
In order to exercise their driving power, they need to become conscious.

32
00:03:24,096 --> 00:03:31,085
To be conscious is to know experience, to hear sounds, feel body sensations, etc.

33
00:03:32,127 --> 00:03:35,510
If we're unconscious, we have no awareness of what's going on.

34
00:03:36,436 --> 00:03:40,733
Consciousness is often likened to a screen on which a movie is projected.

35
00:03:40,752 --> 00:03:45,652
The story of our lives is displayed on the screen of consciousness

36
00:03:48,316 --> 00:03:52,800
In this case consciousness has been hijacked by a Sankara rooted in ignorance.

37
00:03:53,980 --> 00:03:57,144
The Buddha gives this form of consciousness the name Vijnana.

38
00:03:58,185 --> 00:04:03,229
The drive now operating through consciousness wants to play a particular movie on the screen.

39
00:04:03,289 --> 00:04:12,838
A Sankara of greed might want a romantic movie with lots of food and sex, while a Sankara of ill-will would prefer a violent movie.

40
00:04:13,780 --> 00:04:17,242
A Sankara of delusion just wants to control the projector.

41
00:04:18,235 --> 00:04:24,762
It wants to play a movie within the movie, to be the producer, director and central star of all the movies.

42
00:04:27,567 --> 00:04:32,452
For consciousness to manifest in the world, we need both body and mind.

43
00:04:34,295 --> 00:04:36,718
Our bodies are part of the physical world of matter.

44
00:04:37,720 --> 00:04:40,603
Our minds inhabit the world of thought and imagination.

45
00:04:41,925 --> 00:04:47,432
The pair are termed Nama-Rupa and form the fourth link in the wheel.

46
00:04:49,149 --> 00:04:55,478
Rupa gives the three previous links physical reality, which is felt and recognized in our mind .

47
00:04:57,502 --> 00:05:03,310
From this, we can see our emotional life as bodily as well as mental components.

48
00:05:04,733 --> 00:05:10,781
Avijja and Sankara become conscious and can then express themselves through body and mind.

49
00:05:13,485 --> 00:05:17,351
Let's go back to our gardening analogy that we used for the hindrances.

50
00:05:18,040 --> 00:05:20,442
The soil is avicca, ignorance.

51
00:05:21,303 --> 00:05:24,807
It contains seeds of unwholesome sankaras.

52
00:05:26,129 --> 00:05:30,473
These can grow up to be hindrances if they can work their way through the next links.

53
00:05:31,956 --> 00:05:34,278
The seed germinates in consciousness.

54
00:05:35,661 --> 00:05:47,254
If you've watched seeds germinate, you will know that two shoots start to emerge, one growing downwards to become the root system, the other growing upwards towards the light.

55
00:05:47,723 --> 00:05:57,581
This makes for a neat analogy with the subdivision of consciousness into nama-rupa once it comes under the influence of avicca and sankara.

56
00:06:00,581 --> 00:06:04,925
The Sankara now has almost all the apparatus needed to make trouble for us.

57
00:06:06,026 --> 00:06:09,451
It just needs to decide which of our senses to work through.

58
00:06:10,351 --> 00:06:29,930
The tactile sensory system that runs throughout our bodies, or the auditory system ready to receive sounds, or the visual system, taste, smell, or our sixth sense, which is the mind with its feelings, perceptions, moods, emotions and thoughts.

59
00:06:31,665 --> 00:06:35,129
These sense bases form the fifth link in the wheel.

60
00:06:36,810 --> 00:06:42,834
Working through Nama Rupa, consciousness can manifest through any of these systems.

61
00:06:44,997 --> 00:06:48,399
Now our Sankara is ready to sprout into the world.

62
00:06:50,141 --> 00:06:52,403
Say for example it was a seed of greed.

63
00:06:53,103 --> 00:06:55,846
It can now look out greedily through our eyes.

64
00:06:57,067 --> 00:07:01,250
It can search the mind for happy memories or exciting plans.

65
00:07:01,702 --> 00:07:03,846
Similarly for all the other senses.

66
00:07:05,970 --> 00:07:15,605
In our gardening analogy, our seed has found six channels, maybe six little gaps between stones, through which it can sprout up above ground.

67
00:07:18,129 --> 00:07:22,538
This brings us to the sixth link in the wheel, sense contact.

68
00:07:24,139 --> 00:07:28,166
A new bit of sense data impacts on our psychophysical system.

69
00:07:29,497 --> 00:07:34,485
In our experience, all of the first six links arise simultaneously.

70
00:07:36,146 --> 00:07:41,896
We don't experience Avicca on its own, for example, or the Avicca-Sankara combination.

71
00:07:43,177 --> 00:07:50,449
It's only when these meet with the world as it impacts on our senses that we become conscious of all six links.

72
00:07:52,273 --> 00:07:57,680
We can sense these working in combination to colour our experience at any moment.

73
00:07:59,281 --> 00:08:08,252
We might recognise the Sankara of ill-will, for example, and the way it inhabits our body, narrowing our eyes, perhaps, as well as our mind.

74
00:08:09,314 --> 00:08:10,475
Maybe we feel angry.

75
00:08:11,658 --> 00:08:18,987
We might sense some slight uncertainty along with this, or else a bull-headed determination to ignore all obstacles.

76
00:08:19,889 --> 00:08:28,461
Manifestations of Avicca The fact that we are aware of anything is due to consciousness.

77
00:08:29,386 --> 00:08:38,821
so we can trace all of the first six links in our moment-to-moment experience.

78
00:08:38,841 --> 00:08:42,547
I had a good experience of this one time during walking meditation.

79
00:08:43,950 --> 00:08:48,998
I was quite content until someone came into the room making a lot of noise.

80
00:08:49,552 --> 00:08:51,815
I could have sworn the room got darker.

81
00:08:52,917 --> 00:09:05,494
Because of mindfulness I could see that the darkening was internal in my mind, but I was struck at how vividly this was projected into the outside world, as if the sun had gone behind a cloud.

82
00:09:09,418 --> 00:09:12,263
By now we have come halfway around the wheel.

83
00:09:13,865 --> 00:09:18,731
From sense contact onwards the process occurs sequentially.

84
00:09:19,201 --> 00:09:21,884
Let's say the new bit of data was a sound.

85
00:09:23,225 --> 00:09:32,999
As soon as we detect the sound, our cognitive processes go into action, opening the filing cabinet of perception to try to classify it.

86
00:09:34,421 --> 00:09:40,668
What the sankara needs is to have the sound classified as a threat or an opportunity for pleasure.

87
00:09:41,779 --> 00:09:52,796
So cognition compares the sound with those it has previously recognised as threats, such as a loud bang, and opportunities, such as the jingle of the ice cream van.

88
00:09:54,118 --> 00:10:04,091
It also compares with the myriad familiar sounds, like birdsong or distant traffic, which are unimportant in terms of this sanskara's survival.

89
00:10:05,302 --> 00:10:22,187
The new sound can be classified anywhere on a very wide scale, from red alert, major danger, to minor irritation, through unimportant, to mildly pleasant, to wonderful opportunity not to be missed.

90
00:10:23,409 --> 00:10:27,395
This classification gives a hedonic value to the sound.

91
00:10:29,806 --> 00:10:41,982
If you are familiar with this teaching, you'll recognize that what I'm getting at here is vedana, the recognition of any sense contact as pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

92
00:10:43,083 --> 00:10:51,696
Vedana, usually translated as feeling, forms the seventh link in the chain leading from ignorance to dukkha.

93
00:10:53,397 --> 00:11:01,071
Vedana is arguably the most important link for us to recognize because we can stop the wheel turning at this point.

94
00:11:02,553 --> 00:11:06,441
If we can recognize unpleasant sounds, sensations, etc.

95
00:11:06,802 --> 00:11:10,849
without reacting, no dukkha is generated.

96
00:11:14,726 --> 00:11:23,639
Using our gardening analogy, the shoot got its first bit of sunlight and has turned green, so it can be seen by the gardener of mindfulness.

97
00:11:25,243 --> 00:11:34,996
So far it has been concealed underground and we couldn't influence it, but at this point mindfulness can see the shoot and uproot the weed.

98
00:11:37,727 --> 00:11:41,813
Without mindfulness our system automatically reacts to Vedana.

99
00:11:43,176 --> 00:11:50,407
If the sound had been classified as neutral, neither a threat nor an opportunity, our system screens it out.

100
00:11:52,169 --> 00:11:56,817
Consciousness barely registers the sound and it's quickly forgotten.

101
00:11:58,062 --> 00:12:08,500
This is an example of neutral Vedana and the reaction of delusion, ignoring most of our experience, only barely conscious of our environment.

102
00:12:10,263 --> 00:12:13,207
This isn't the same as letting go of the sound mindfully.

103
00:12:13,227 --> 00:12:17,235
It's an act of ignoring, a form of suppression.

104
00:12:18,758 --> 00:12:21,302
The sound isn't allowed to get any attention.

105
00:12:22,480 --> 00:12:32,216
If we were to look more closely at such sounds, we might find judgments like unimportant or boring backing up the neutral classification.

106
00:12:33,759 --> 00:12:42,075
This is due to the work of our Sankara seed, jealously guarding consciousness so that the screen will only play a movie it enjoys.

107
00:12:44,840 --> 00:12:54,193
On the other hand, if the sound was recognised as our favourite music, this will be classified as an opportunity for pleasure, pleasant vedana.

108
00:12:55,495 --> 00:12:57,759
Our system will be stimulated to perk up.

109
00:12:58,620 --> 00:12:59,822
We listen avidly.

110
00:13:00,962 --> 00:13:02,806
This is the reaction of desire.

111
00:13:02,846 --> 00:13:07,572
Our system's first step in getting what it wants.

112
00:13:09,611 --> 00:13:16,966
When desire is strong, it can be felt as a strong flow of energy in the body and a focusing effect in the mind.

113
00:13:18,149 --> 00:13:24,221
The mind starting to zoom in on whatever it wants, magnifying this in consciousness.

114
00:13:27,868 --> 00:13:30,472
Now let's say the sound was a loud bang.

115
00:13:31,870 --> 00:13:39,783
Cognition classifies this as a red alert and our whole system vibrates with shock, waking us up to the danger.

116
00:13:39,842 --> 00:13:47,134
This is the fight or flight response and hormones may be released to stimulate and energise us.

117
00:13:48,456 --> 00:13:55,126
We start to tense up as unpleasant sensations prolong and amplify the original red alert response.

118
00:13:56,474 --> 00:14:03,210
This is the reaction of aversion, our system's first step in trying to cope with danger.

119
00:14:03,269 --> 00:14:12,913
Aversion is actually another form of desire, the desire to get rid of what we dislike.

120
00:14:15,475 --> 00:14:27,067
As we bring our attention to the sensations of breathing, we can experience the three links of contact, vedana and any reactions of desire or aversion.

121
00:14:29,650 --> 00:14:33,274
Sense contact reveals the rising and falling sensations.

122
00:14:34,716 --> 00:14:39,761
Then there is the cognition of these as pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

123
00:14:41,041 --> 00:14:45,885
So far we have two links, contact and feeling.

124
00:14:47,947 --> 00:14:54,673
It is very beneficial to rest attention here and learn to differentiate these two from desire.

125
00:14:57,157 --> 00:15:02,182
We feel desire as a disturbance that quickly turns the wheel towards dukkha.

126
00:15:03,523 --> 00:15:10,710
This gives a visceral illustration of the second noble truth that desire is the cause of suffering.

127
00:15:13,475 --> 00:15:20,086
When we sense the disturbing effect of desire, we can at times be persuaded to relax and let go.

128
00:15:20,126 --> 00:15:23,852
We feel the benefit as deeper tranquility.

129
00:15:25,635 --> 00:15:34,892
Sometimes our system oscillates between the tranquility afforded by letting the wheels stop at Vedana and little jabs of desire that lead to dukkha.

130
00:15:36,086 --> 00:15:49,538
At such times our system is reinforcing its understanding of the second and third noble truths that desire is the cause of suffering and that letting go of desire brings an end to suffering.

131
00:15:55,163 --> 00:15:59,527
If we're not being mindful the wheel continues inexorably towards dukkha.

132
00:16:00,628 --> 00:16:03,971
The next link is termed clinging or attaching.

133
00:16:05,351 --> 00:16:05,993
We become attached

134
00:16:08,807 --> 00:16:13,774
Attachment brings up a sense of self to protect and guard our position.

135
00:16:15,355 --> 00:16:18,178
If we're mindful, we can feel this happening.

136
00:16:19,720 --> 00:16:26,307
Let's look at how a sense of self might manifest as a result of pleasant, unpleasant and neutral feeling.

137
00:16:29,150 --> 00:16:30,393
Say we get a compliment.

138
00:16:31,113 --> 00:16:33,956
Lots of lovely feelings may manifest as a result.

139
00:16:34,798 --> 00:16:36,840
You might feel energised.

140
00:16:37,477 --> 00:16:43,206
There may be a sense of expanding, growing taller, as well as a sense of power and control.

141
00:16:43,225 --> 00:16:48,133
I like Gregory Cramer's description of this as puffing up.

142
00:16:50,417 --> 00:16:55,283
On the other hand, suppose you're waiting at a bus stop, just idling the time away.

143
00:16:56,245 --> 00:17:01,653
You're vaguely aware of your body, the passing traffic and the scene around you, but not interested in these.

144
00:17:02,833 --> 00:17:06,759
Instead, you're planning the rest of your day, after the bus comes.

145
00:17:07,481 --> 00:17:11,166
Here we have an example of how Sankara can feed on neutral feelings.

146
00:17:12,328 --> 00:17:17,556
The incoming sense data cannot satisfy its needs and so this is suppressed.

147
00:17:18,438 --> 00:17:21,821
Instead, the seed sprouts through the channel of the mind.

148
00:17:23,203 --> 00:17:28,873
Here it finds the excitement and pleasure it desires in the ability of the mind to imagine and plan.

149
00:17:29,894 --> 00:17:31,296
Do you remember Walter Mitty?

150
00:17:32,997 --> 00:17:42,708
If you read the story or saw the movie, you will recognise him as a caricature of delusion, pouncing on every idle moment to indulge his fantasy life.

151
00:17:47,232 --> 00:17:54,961
Suppose, as you're idling away at the bus stop, a car passes at speed, splashing you with water from a puddle, drenching your trousers.

152
00:17:56,044 --> 00:17:59,847
This time you might feel yourself deflating rather than puffing up.

153
00:18:01,532 --> 00:18:05,000
This is the emergence of self resulting from aversion.

154
00:18:06,223 --> 00:18:08,489
It can feel like the air going out of a balloon.

155
00:18:08,528 --> 00:18:13,179
The deflation may implode to form a tight constriction.

156
00:18:14,201 --> 00:18:15,704
Your face tenses angrily.

157
00:18:15,744 --> 00:18:21,076
You might feel constricted within your skin facing a hostile world outside.

158
00:18:23,166 --> 00:18:27,873
These are all examples of clinging or attaching, opadana in Pali.

159
00:18:29,074 --> 00:18:32,898
At this step we have the emergence of a sense of self.

160
00:18:34,681 --> 00:18:44,112
The mind does a bit more shuffling around in its enormous filing cabinet and decides to classify the incoming sense data as me or mine.

161
00:18:45,256 --> 00:18:54,290
When we get the compliment, instead of simply feeling happy and gratified that something has turned out well, we think it is me who is being complimented.

162
00:18:55,853 --> 00:19:04,186
This sense of me quickly projects itself into the future and we start feeling powerful and thinking we will always be able to do so well.

163
00:19:04,207 --> 00:19:09,474
A very nice way to feel, if only it weren't based on delusion.

164
00:19:10,788 --> 00:19:20,946
When we suppress neutral sensations in order to daydream, the pleasure of being idle is perceived as me who has the power to think and plan and daydream.

165
00:19:22,830 --> 00:19:28,161
When we cling to anger at the careless driver, we take their carelessness personally.

166
00:19:29,102 --> 00:19:32,188
So we don't just get wet, we get insulted.

167
00:19:34,497 --> 00:19:37,580
In our gardening analogy, the weed has blossomed.

168
00:19:38,722 --> 00:19:42,489
It's fully developed and is ready to start sowing its seeds.

169
00:19:45,252 --> 00:19:48,037
Our sense of self initiates the next link.

170
00:19:48,657 --> 00:19:52,462
Bhava in Pali is usually translated as becoming.

171
00:19:54,065 --> 00:19:55,988
We experience this as willpower.

172
00:19:57,711 --> 00:20:01,415
The self puts its stamp on the world by an effort of will.

173
00:20:02,644 --> 00:20:07,352
Up till now the Sankara is held as a potential within our body and mind.

174
00:20:08,212 --> 00:20:10,115
Now comes the moment for action.

175
00:20:11,698 --> 00:20:17,045
We might shake our fists at the careless driver, hurl insults towards the back of their car.

176
00:20:18,426 --> 00:20:24,214
We might smile at the person who paid us the compliment and bring a more animated tone into the conversation.

177
00:20:25,737 --> 00:20:27,640
Even thoughts are willed.

178
00:20:28,446 --> 00:20:33,334
They don't emerge spontaneously from our mind, but from the intention to think.

179
00:20:35,057 --> 00:20:39,442
Willpower keeps us idling at the bus stop, imagining the rest of our day.

180
00:20:39,502 --> 00:20:46,994
Think of the effort of will it takes to stop this, to be mindful instead of being lost in thought.

181
00:20:47,035 --> 00:20:53,964
This gives us some idea of the strength of will fuelling idle thoughts.

182
00:20:56,746 --> 00:21:00,790
In our gardening analogy, the weed is now sowing its seeds.

183
00:21:02,333 --> 00:21:06,617
Each effort of will drops a new seed into the soil of ignorance.

184
00:21:07,880 --> 00:21:12,164
As we indulge hatred, we sow Sankara seeds of hatred.

185
00:21:13,807 --> 00:21:15,990
Similarly for greed and delusion.

186
00:21:17,632 --> 00:21:22,878
We shape our own character in the multitude of moments in which we exercise our will.

187
00:21:24,141 --> 00:21:25,301
A sobering thought.

188
00:21:26,632 --> 00:21:28,714
I'll say more about this tomorrow night.

189
00:21:31,778 --> 00:21:36,806
Once we have exercised our will, something new starts to manifest in the world.

190
00:21:38,048 --> 00:21:41,031
This is the penultimate link, termed birth.

191
00:21:42,733 --> 00:21:52,587
Say the seed of greed was at the base of this particular turn of the wheel and it found its outlet in reaction to the alluring smell of pizza.

192
00:21:53,429 --> 00:21:57,275
The self forms and wills us to get that pizza into our mouth.

193
00:21:58,215 --> 00:22:02,541
Thus the whole process of purchasing and eating a pizza is born.

194
00:22:04,705 --> 00:22:17,344
If instead the seed of ill will had found its outlet in the careless driver, an angry self forms, angry thoughts are willed into being and a storm of rage initiates.

195
00:22:19,686 --> 00:22:33,845
Whenever the seed of delusion finds a mind willing to indulge it, we generate a stream of thoughts and images and we start planning or daydreaming or worrying, whatever is our favourite pastime in idle moments.

196
00:22:36,268 --> 00:22:44,377
The chain of events which we have just started gives our Sankara lots and lots of opportunities to sow more seeds.

197
00:22:46,535 --> 00:22:50,760
But every birth leads to death, the last link in the chain.

198
00:22:52,303 --> 00:22:57,530
Our idle plans and dreams fall apart when we get that splash from the passing car.

199
00:22:58,873 --> 00:23:05,883
Our pizza heaven disintegrates when all that's left on our plate is a few smears of tomato paste.

200
00:23:05,903 --> 00:23:16,018
Our bus stop rage could deflate into embarrassment if the car stops, the driver gets out to apologise and we realise we're hurling insults at our neighbour.

201
00:23:18,326 --> 00:23:20,990
With death comes all the dukkha of dying.

202
00:23:22,472 --> 00:23:27,339
The enticing pizza turns into a bloated tummy and worries about putting on weight.

203
00:23:28,642 --> 00:23:32,467
The plans for our day rarely work out quite so easily as we expect.

204
00:23:33,469 --> 00:23:37,855
The bout of rage ends up giving us a headache and raises our blood pressure.

205
00:23:41,023 --> 00:23:49,172
We can sometimes identify these later links from contact onwards to dukkha while emotions fade away in mindful awareness.

206
00:23:50,634 --> 00:23:55,159
Say, for example, I've been clinging to rage over some troubling memory.

207
00:23:55,179 --> 00:24:00,183
A strong sense of self insists on my viewpoint in the affair.

208
00:24:00,243 --> 00:24:03,928
I feel self-righteous and indignant.

209
00:24:05,189 --> 00:24:09,292
I can't understand how the other person could have behaved so badly.

210
00:24:10,942 --> 00:24:16,167
Mindfulness shows me the effort and strain needed to maintain my self-righteous stance.

211
00:24:17,308 --> 00:24:24,055
I feel the tensions running through my body, the fear and confusion that are maintaining my sense of enmity.

212
00:24:25,195 --> 00:24:29,759
I am witnessing the stage of dukkha, the final link in the chain.

213
00:24:31,381 --> 00:24:39,127
Sadly, I admit to myself that the effort is too much, that it's taking up all my energy and not getting me anywhere.

214
00:24:39,377 --> 00:24:42,001
I realise I will have to let go.

215
00:24:44,346 --> 00:24:48,211
Sometimes the emotion simply dissolves at that point.

216
00:24:49,473 --> 00:24:55,584
At other times, when the emotion has really run deep, letting go is a very gradual process.

217
00:24:57,426 --> 00:25:03,596
Although this prolongs the pain, it also helps me clarify the earlier stages in the wheel.

218
00:25:06,259 --> 00:25:14,128
Once I decide to let go, there is a slight loosening of tension and I now have the mental space to see more clearly.

219
00:25:15,670 --> 00:25:21,217
I feel the allure of self-righteousness, how wonderful it is to be morally superior.

220
00:25:22,798 --> 00:25:26,201
What I am now feeling is the dukkha associated with birth.

221
00:25:28,104 --> 00:25:34,191
I no longer want this particular birth into self-righteousness and rage, but I have no choice in the matter.

222
00:25:35,182 --> 00:25:38,125
Thoughts condemning the other person hammer through my mind.

223
00:25:39,467 --> 00:25:48,115
I feel the intense pressure pushing my face into a grimace, pushing my stomach into a knot, pushing the thoughts into my mind.

224
00:25:50,517 --> 00:25:58,163
As I watch this mindfully, the emotion loses power and the thoughts dwindle down to an attempt to sink them.

225
00:25:59,684 --> 00:26:02,607
I can sense willpower pushing the thoughts into being.

226
00:26:03,819 --> 00:26:10,622
Because of mindfulness, they now can't get much further than a sort of jabbering, you, you, you.

227
00:26:10,662 --> 00:26:15,096
What is clarifying for me here is the link of becoming.

228
00:26:15,346 --> 00:26:19,833
the way we push our emotions out into the world by an effort of will.

229
00:26:19,853 --> 00:26:29,887
I also feel the pain of each little jabber, each attempt to define myself as separate from the other person.

230
00:26:31,109 --> 00:26:34,114
So this is the dukkha associated with becoming.

231
00:26:36,423 --> 00:26:45,574
In time, that effort of will too fades away, and I'm left in a perplexed state, trying to hold myself together.

232
00:26:45,614 --> 00:26:48,978
No thoughts form at this stage.

233
00:26:49,719 --> 00:26:51,180
It's as if I'm mesmerized.

234
00:26:52,342 --> 00:26:54,584
My mind has no flexibility to think.

235
00:26:55,586 --> 00:26:57,268
I'm usually holding my breath too.

236
00:26:58,269 --> 00:26:59,410
I feel totally stuck.

237
00:27:01,599 --> 00:27:06,047
What I'm experiencing here is the dukkha associated with clinging.

238
00:27:07,208 --> 00:27:20,367
My system is stuck in body and in mind as desire fastens me to what it desires, in this case to rewrite the past, to rid myself of the painful memory.

239
00:27:23,977 --> 00:27:27,923
Eventually, the need to breathe overcomes the attachment.

240
00:27:28,825 --> 00:27:33,772
I feel my stuck state dissolve as I take those first tentative breaths.

241
00:27:34,954 --> 00:27:42,847
The sense of self fades and instead I feel a strong pushing sensation in my body that I recognise as aversion.

242
00:27:44,250 --> 00:27:50,220
I feel my attempts to push against the painful memory, to shut it out from consciousness.

243
00:27:52,106 --> 00:28:01,205
This is the link of desire, in this case in its negative form of aversion, the desire to get rid of the painful memory.

244
00:28:05,859 --> 00:28:17,263
If I can hold attention steady on this pushing sensation, it eventually relaxes and I sense the painful memory and the bare sensations involved in grief.

245
00:28:18,547 --> 00:28:26,383
But there is some flow now, the memory can flow through my mind and unpleasant sensations flow through the body.

246
00:28:26,363 --> 00:28:30,868
I might react occasionally and feel the dukkha of enmity.

247
00:28:31,971 --> 00:28:40,903
This is now so obviously futile and painful that I'm persuaded to relax again and open to the grief and the painful memory.

248
00:28:43,067 --> 00:28:46,531
These are the stages of contact and feeling.

249
00:28:47,827 --> 00:28:49,911
I feel the sensations of grief.

250
00:28:50,832 --> 00:28:55,640
I am aware of the memory and also of the unpleasantness of the whole experience.

251
00:28:57,201 --> 00:29:02,229
But because I know the pain and futility of aversion, I do not react.

252
00:29:03,310 --> 00:29:05,954
Wisdom overcomes aversion.

253
00:29:05,934 --> 00:29:20,484
If I can hold steady on that kernel of not wanting, it dissolves moment after moment as it contacts the painful memory and the sensations of grief.

254
00:29:22,861 --> 00:29:37,178
The seeds of ill-will are still sprouting in the seedbed of ignorance, hijacking consciousness for their favourite movie, finding their outlets in the emotion of grief and the pain of the memory.

255
00:29:38,538 --> 00:29:41,202
But the wheel stops at Vedana.

256
00:29:42,865 --> 00:29:49,172
Aversion is not being generated and therefore the wheel cannot turn towards Dukkha.

257
00:29:49,777 --> 00:29:55,084
The process is now sensed as a healing one and compassion arises.

258
00:29:57,346 --> 00:30:01,792
Sooner or later, I start to see things from the other person's point of view.

259
00:30:04,757 --> 00:30:16,492
As we watch the wheel turn and get to know the feel of its various links, we're also cleaning up the seedbed of ignorance, the first link in the chain.

260
00:30:17,451 --> 00:30:23,959
Our understanding of the Dhamma is increasing and so ignorance is transforming to wisdom.

261
00:30:25,641 --> 00:30:29,345
Thus the wheel gets fewer chances to start turning.

262
00:30:32,469 --> 00:30:36,752
What can we say about those moments when the wheel isn't actively turning?

263
00:30:38,775 --> 00:30:44,741
This brings us to the third noble truth that there is an end to suffering.

264
00:30:46,644 --> 00:30:51,491
Our task, according to the Buddha, is to realize this for ourselves.

265
00:30:57,179 --> 00:31:00,242
So far, I've been talking about the experience of dukkha.

266
00:31:01,244 --> 00:31:07,393
To get to know the Third Noble Truth, we have to sensitize ourselves to the absence of dukkha.

267
00:31:09,336 --> 00:31:14,863
One danger that's easy to fall into is to over-dramatize this experience.

268
00:31:15,416 --> 00:31:19,884
The end of dukkha is the culmination of all our training, our years of practice.

269
00:31:20,506 --> 00:31:26,194
So surely it should come with loud applause, hoops of delight, balloons and fireworks.

270
00:31:27,396 --> 00:31:34,008
But in fact we sense the absence of dukkha in quiet moments that don't call for any special attention.

271
00:31:35,170 --> 00:31:37,914
Just to acknowledge the moment is enough.

272
00:31:38,806 --> 00:31:47,160
the penny drops, we realize Nibbana is close at hand, there for the taking, our natural state.

273
00:31:49,683 --> 00:32:01,303
Another way we screen out those quiet moments is to expect ourselves to be totally enlightened, or at least three-quarters way there, before we experience the end of dukkha.

274
00:32:02,042 --> 00:32:12,634
Now of course there will for all of us be that wonderful moment when the teaching finally clicks into place and we know for certain that desire will never trouble us again.

275
00:32:12,694 --> 00:32:24,709
But even in our present unenlightened state we can experience fleeting moments when desire is stilled, when dukkha is not showing up.

276
00:32:28,586 --> 00:32:34,273
There are various reflections that help develop our taste for quietness and the absence of drama.

277
00:32:36,195 --> 00:32:39,279
One is the translation of Nibbāna as cooling.

278
00:32:39,319 --> 00:32:44,767
The Buddha describes our unenlightened state as one of burning.

279
00:32:44,807 --> 00:32:48,131
All our senses are burning with desire.

280
00:32:49,251 --> 00:32:54,038
Unwittingly we keep loading on more fuel because of our attachments.

281
00:32:54,980 --> 00:33:00,385
But as we learn to let go, the fuel store is gradually burning out.

282
00:33:01,586 --> 00:33:02,807
We are cooling down.

283
00:33:02,847 --> 00:33:05,250
Nibbana-ing, you could say.

284
00:33:07,913 --> 00:33:10,615
As our passions cool off, what remains?

285
00:33:12,278 --> 00:33:14,941
Nibbana is often described by absence.

286
00:33:15,580 --> 00:33:21,847
The absence of ageing, death, pain and any other form of suffering, for example.

287
00:33:22,839 --> 00:33:26,534
also the absence of what we would not normally think of as suffering.

288
00:33:28,259 --> 00:33:32,394
Here is an extract from one description the Buddha gave of Nibbana.

289
00:33:34,265 --> 00:33:49,625
There is, Bhikkhus, that base where there is no earth, no water, no fire, no air, neither this world, nor another world, nor both, neither sun nor moon.

290
00:33:50,827 --> 00:34:01,301
Here, Bhikkhus, I say, there is no coming, no going, no staying, no deceasing, no uprising.

291
00:34:02,394 --> 00:34:06,704
not fixed, not movable, it has no support.

292
00:34:08,389 --> 00:34:12,177
Just this is the end of suffering.

293
00:34:16,867 --> 00:34:20,876
This description is perplexing, bewildering even.

294
00:34:21,784 --> 00:34:29,514
Remember that the Buddha first thought that the enlightened state he had discovered was too subtle to be understood by others.

295
00:34:30,635 --> 00:34:34,099
Hearing this description of Nibbana, who could blame him?

296
00:34:36,021 --> 00:34:41,646
Although the description is perplexing, I also find it intriguing and inspiring.

297
00:34:43,289 --> 00:34:44,990
I'm drawn towards the mystery.

298
00:34:46,101 --> 00:34:51,869
but it can also stir grief and anger because we think of absence in terms of loss.

299
00:34:54,612 --> 00:34:57,094
Could absence actually satisfy us?

300
00:34:58,675 --> 00:35:02,760
That would entail a huge shift in our normal way of seeing things.

301
00:35:04,302 --> 00:35:09,949
But we can tiptoe towards this mystery by learning to appreciate absences.

302
00:35:11,059 --> 00:35:15,065
The Buddha specifically asks us to do this in terms of our mind states.

303
00:35:15,987 --> 00:35:28,103
For example, we are to notice the mind state of greed and the mind state of non-greed, the mind state of hatred and the mind state of non-hatred.

304
00:35:29,784 --> 00:35:33,771
We would rarely ask ourselves what is not in our minds at the moment.

305
00:35:35,112 --> 00:35:39,057
But it is part of the practice which sensitizes us to Nibbana.

306
00:35:39,663 --> 00:35:48,760
So whenever you are feeling relaxed, see can you note that you don't feel greedy right now and that you don't feel angry right now.

307
00:35:48,800 --> 00:35:53,411
Thus we can deepen our appreciation of the state.

308
00:35:55,896 --> 00:35:59,443
We can also take note of the ending of any hindrance.

309
00:36:00,148 --> 00:36:04,934
If someone or something annoys us, we might be plagued by irritation for hours.

310
00:36:05,516 --> 00:36:06,336
Then it passes.

311
00:36:06,978 --> 00:36:08,780
We hardly notice the transition.

312
00:36:09,521 --> 00:36:14,748
But it's a very good time to be noting how pleasant it is not to feel irritated.

313
00:36:14,768 --> 00:36:21,476
The recent memory of how irritating it was to feel irritated helps us appreciate the absence.

314
00:36:23,498 --> 00:36:26,021
I frequently get cramps in my feet.

315
00:36:26,373 --> 00:36:31,297
I used to dread these until I started using them as a Vipassana focus.

316
00:36:32,259 --> 00:36:37,143
It amazed me how quickly the pain diminished as I focused on it mindfully.

317
00:36:37,182 --> 00:36:42,307
It also intrigued me to find the moment when pain faded away.

318
00:36:42,327 --> 00:36:52,177
I noticed how my mind distanced itself as soon as pain started to fade, wanting to find something more interesting to latch on to.

319
00:36:53,557 --> 00:37:00,349
It became a good exercise for me to see could I keep track of those lingering sensations until they faded away.

320
00:37:00,389 --> 00:37:06,440
We can practice this with any disturbance, mental or physical.

321
00:37:07,581 --> 00:37:10,487
That moment where desire fades away, for example.

322
00:37:11,378 --> 00:37:15,806
One moment we were disturbed by our longing for something, the next moment we weren't.

323
00:37:16,806 --> 00:37:23,097
It's so easy to miss these fleeting moments of peace as we hurl ourselves forward into the next challenge.

324
00:37:24,260 --> 00:37:31,092
But we need to pause for a moment to feel the momentary absence of trouble and learn to appreciate this.

325
00:37:33,382 --> 00:37:37,268
Renunciation gives us an opportunity to practice with absences.

326
00:37:38,351 --> 00:37:39,833
This time we're being creative.

327
00:37:40,494 --> 00:37:45,922
We are creating an absence, a precious space which attunes us to nibbana.

328
00:37:47,123 --> 00:37:53,653
If we decide not to watch TV for an hour some evening, a whole new space opens up in our lives.

329
00:37:55,217 --> 00:38:01,786
If we decide not to eat an extra biscuit, we're diminishing the power of greed as a disturbance in our psyche.

330
00:38:03,235 --> 00:38:08,121
Refraining from backbiting a person who annoyed us gives space for forgiveness to grow.

331
00:38:08,141 --> 00:38:13,927
These sound easy but are quite challenging for most of us.

332
00:38:15,369 --> 00:38:19,773
It takes continual mindfulness to refrain from whatever is tempting us.

333
00:38:21,016 --> 00:38:28,905
Any little slip and we're turning on the TV, gobbling the biscuit and passing a disparaging remark about the person who has annoyed us.

334
00:38:30,539 --> 00:38:39,349
The reward for annunciation is not immediately obvious whereas the TV, the biscuit and the catty remark all provide instant gratification.

335
00:38:40,871 --> 00:38:46,657
We need to fortify ourselves by considering the long-term benefits of a more peaceful mind.

336
00:38:49,320 --> 00:38:57,610
Sometimes in meditation we feel the urge towards greed, hatred or delusion but have the resources to resist these.

337
00:38:58,652 --> 00:39:04,704
For example, while we are watching the breath, we might feel the desire to stray into thoughts and fantasy.

338
00:39:05,885 --> 00:39:14,963
It can feel as though my chest, head and neck are almost straining to lift off, tear away from the abdomen with its rhythmic, calming sensations.

339
00:39:16,525 --> 00:39:20,914
The energy accumulates in my head and I sense the urgent need to think.

340
00:39:21,822 --> 00:39:25,418
If I can catch all this, I can usually resist the temptation.

341
00:39:25,460 --> 00:39:29,739
The note, not indulging, not indulging, can help.

342
00:39:31,052 --> 00:39:35,000
This gives me a more visceral feel for the benefits of renunciation.

343
00:39:36,342 --> 00:39:43,833
I sense the tranquility on offer from the sensations of breathing and counteracting desire for heady excitement.

344
00:39:45,757 --> 00:39:53,871
It's so obvious looking at this that the rhythm of the breath is more deeply satisfying than indulging desire.

345
00:39:55,284 --> 00:40:01,835
Although this can bring up the grief of renunciation, it also helps me choose not to indulge desire.

346
00:40:01,855 --> 00:40:10,248
As well as strengthening willpower for renunciation, this nurtures the taste for absence.

347
00:40:11,329 --> 00:40:14,193
It helps us question our preoccupation with clinging.

348
00:40:15,856 --> 00:40:18,360
Why does life need to be so full of pleasure?

349
00:40:18,420 --> 00:40:23,047
It takes so much energy to hold on to pleasure.

350
00:40:24,360 --> 00:40:28,565
Is there a possibility of letting it come and go without so much fuss?

351
00:40:30,969 --> 00:40:34,293
We can cultivate a taste for absence at other levels in life.

352
00:40:35,554 --> 00:40:44,724
One teacher described how, having taken down an ugly shed in his back garden, he spent several days looking out the window and enjoying the absence of the shed.

353
00:40:44,764 --> 00:40:54,215
In my own case, now that I can no longer talk easily, I can sometimes enjoy the absence of talking.

354
00:40:55,528 --> 00:40:59,695
Before the operation, I would have enjoyed the buzz of conversation.

355
00:41:01,317 --> 00:41:11,951
While I still grieve the loss of this great joy in my life, I also appreciate the fact that there are now more moments of peace in the company of family and friends.

356
00:41:13,233 --> 00:41:15,856
I'm hoping others may also feel this benefit.

357
00:41:17,998 --> 00:41:24,608
For the first months, I couldn't use the electrolarynx and used to carry around a whiteboard and marker everywhere.

358
00:41:25,550 --> 00:41:37,793
A friend later remarked that when he saw me coming into a party with my whiteboard and marker, that he felt relieved, looking forward to those relaxing moments of silence while people waited for me to write.

359
00:41:39,315 --> 00:41:48,552
I am sure you all sense the benefit of not talking while you are here in retreat, and sense the benefit of this particular renunciation.

360
00:41:51,199 --> 00:41:56,110
Another contemplation I found helpful is on the physical space between things.

361
00:41:57,594 --> 00:42:03,327
As we look around us, it's generally the objects we see, not the spaces between them.

362
00:42:04,710 --> 00:42:06,213
But what if there was no space?

363
00:42:07,096 --> 00:42:08,179
Imagine the clutter.

364
00:42:08,880 --> 00:42:10,103
We couldn't move.

365
00:42:10,657 --> 00:42:14,704
To find our way from one place to another, we seek out space.

366
00:42:15,806 --> 00:42:20,032
We actively search for absence, for the gaps between things.

367
00:42:21,375 --> 00:42:29,829
It's only these spaces that have the potential to receive our body as it moves, to let it go as it passes by.

368
00:42:33,487 --> 00:42:49,724
Noticing and appreciating space, gaps, absence of difficulties, the ending of pain and emotional disturbance, the peace of not doing, all sensitize us to the third noble truth, the end of suffering.

369
00:42:51,224 --> 00:43:11,005
These unobtrusive, non-dramatic phenomena, so easy to ignore, have nonetheless the potential to alter the course of our lives, to reveal the quiet mystery at the heart of life and death, the stillness that penetrates all things.

370
00:43:14,900 --> 00:43:27,492
Before finishing, I'd like to focus on that crucial mid-section of the wheel and show its potential to reveal second and third noble truths as they show up in our experience.

371
00:43:30,019 --> 00:43:33,344
Let's recap on the wheel using our gardening analogy.

372
00:43:33,385 --> 00:43:39,173
The soil of ignorance holds seeds of the unwholesome sankaras.

373
00:43:40,536 --> 00:43:51,994
To get the wheel turning, one of these germinates in consciousness, implants itself in our body and mind to search through our senses for satisfaction.

374
00:43:51,974 --> 00:44:00,987
A sense of greed looks for pleasure, generates the desire for more, and a sense of self emerges to consume the pleasure.

375
00:44:02,688 --> 00:44:07,815
A seed of ill-will looks for displeasure, thriving in the battle to destroy and vanquish.

376
00:44:08,777 --> 00:44:13,965
It stimulates aversion and a sense of self emerges to fight its battles.

377
00:44:16,443 --> 00:44:22,880
A seed of delusion looks for neutral Vedana, thriving in the security of our imagination.

378
00:44:22,920 --> 00:44:27,431
We are always the boss, protected from reality.

379
00:44:33,907 --> 00:44:39,315
Once the Sankara has blossomed into a self, it gets to work sowing new seeds.

380
00:44:40,336 --> 00:44:47,005
The willpower needed to drive each thought, word and action drops another seed into the soil of ignorance.

381
00:44:48,327 --> 00:44:55,697
And as the thoughts, words and actions manifest in the world, they initiate a chain of events.

382
00:44:56,757 --> 00:44:59,681
A seed of greed might get us gobbling some biscuits.

383
00:45:00,420 --> 00:45:03,025
A seed of hatred might get us into a tantrum.

384
00:45:03,846 --> 00:45:08,150
A seed of delusion lulls us into a spiral of thought and imagination.

385
00:45:08,210 --> 00:45:21,347
Dukkha emerges as the biscuits transform into indigestion, as the tantrum turns into spoiled friendships, as Walter Mitty falls down to earth.

386
00:45:23,824 --> 00:45:29,592
The remedy for this never-ending round of misery is, of course, mindfulness.

387
00:45:31,717 --> 00:45:44,414
Mindfulness of dukkha is one starting place, or, whenever possible, mindfulness of sense contact and vedana, the point before the seeds have had a chance to blossom.

388
00:45:45,947 --> 00:45:53,960
If we can hold attention steady there, unwholesome Sankaras don't get a chance to spread their seeds.

389
00:45:56,525 --> 00:46:02,213
At times we can grow quite peaceful, feeling the flow of sensations and feelings.

390
00:46:03,074 --> 00:46:09,525
Then a little prickle of desire emerges, prompting us to hold on to the peace.

391
00:46:09,690 --> 00:46:14,177
We sense the disturbance, the budding anxiety that edges desire.

392
00:46:14,217 --> 00:46:26,096
If we can note desire, desire, watching the disturbance as it manifests, it eventually fades away, leaving us in peace again.

393
00:46:27,717 --> 00:46:34,668
Here we have the second and third noble truth manifesting in our experience.

394
00:46:35,661 --> 00:46:43,733
We sense for ourselves that desire causes suffering and that letting go of desire ends suffering.

395
00:46:45,213 --> 00:46:46,275
It's as simple as that.

396
00:46:47,396 --> 00:46:49,159
Simple but not easy.

397
00:46:51,242 --> 00:47:03,237
I hope this reflection on the second and third truths helps us trust our underlying simplicity, our natural beauty, our birthright of ease.

398
00:47:05,750 --> 00:47:11,996
May we and all beings be free from suffering.

